node.text:
Stuart demonstrates exactly how to use a HAIMER Presetter to get offsets. This can be done while the CNC Machine is cutting chips and making money. When the machine is ready to change jobs, you simply load the new tools, while all offsets are transferred to the machine automatically. This allows for a much shorter set up time and keeps the CNC Machine making money.

node.text:
CNC Machining a custom probe for our Walter Helitronic Vision 400L CNC Grinding Machine…

Programmed in Mastercam

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Titan Gilroy in Flower Mound, Texas. May be an image of 2 people and beard.

node.text:
It was an Honor to show Jeff Weaver around our new shop yesterday. 

17 years ago this Amazing Manual Machinist took a chance on a young CNC Machinist with Huge dreams of Changing The World…

Invested every penny he had in my Vision and took his hands off the wheel and allowed me to do my thing…

2 years later, He took the money he made from our deal, and purchased a new house in Texas and retired with his wonderful wife Elena.

15 years later… (Yesterday)
He drove in Texas… 30 minutes to the new shop just built by that “Not” so young CNC Machinist.

Jeff, as I said yesterday…
I Love you and it’s my Honor to have you as one of my closest friends in this world.

Your wrong when you said… “Anyone would have done what I did”…

No body else did.. “You Did”
And it changed my life, my families lives… and now what we created is changing countless lives…

Love you Brother😁

PS. Look closely at his hat… its a hat from when we first started…

Proudly stating… “CNC EXPERTS”

How fitting is it… that our new Certifications platform is call just that… “CNC EXPERT”

BOOM!!!

Time saved on setups = $$$. Definitely a fan of quick change systems... 

Travis setting up a Kennametal KM50 Holder w/ the Quick Change Kennametal TACU System. 

Such a beast combo for our lathes and been seeing articles online of this combo making a big difference in helping shops compete across the country and world. 

Machine: Doosan PUMA 2600SY
Coolant: Blaser Synergy 735
Material: 316 Stainless Steel

CNC Machining fast-forwarded just for visual purposes…

node.text:
Ceramic tooling is highly efficient when it comes to CNC machining Inconel and other nickel based super alloys…

Ceramics are also known for their fireworks show… meaning they are always ran dry and turn into a ball of flames as they engage the material. Don’t be alarmed though as ceramics are chemically inert. The tool material does not heat up at all and instead dispels the heat from the cut.

Although Ceramics run faster than carbide tools, their life span in cut is considerably less. Companies that have a ton of Inconel to machine should be using ceramics… but trust me, there is a science involved. Pro-Tip: Many use tool management in the CNC to run efficiently… meaning they will load 5 endmills at a time and give each a life expectancy… and then each tool runs right after the last to get the necessary material removal.
